2026-03-09 | Lexicographically Largest String with At Most One Swap

Question
Return the lexicographically largest string obtainable by performing at most one swap.

	Approach
1.	Record the last occurrence of each character in the string.
2.	Traverse the string from left to right.
3.	For each position i:
		check if there exists a larger character ('z' → s[i]+1)
		that appears later in the string.
4.	If such a character exists:
		swap current character with the farthest occurrence
		of the largest possible character.
5.	Return the resulting string immediately after the swap.
6.	If no beneficial swap exists, return the original string.

	Time Complexity
	O(n * 26) ≈ O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(26)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    string largestString(string s) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<int> last(26, -1);

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            last[s[i] - 'a'] = i;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int c = 25; c > s[i] - 'a'; c--) {
                if (last[c] > i) {
                    swap(s[i], s[last[c]]);
                    return s;
                }
            }
        }

        return s;
    }
};

	Key Insight
To maximize lexicographic order, we should swap the earliest possible character with the largest character appearing later in the string.  
Tracking the last occurrence ensures we get the greatest possible improvement with a single swap.
